        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>The <strong>Google Possum Update</strong> was a local search algorithm change in September 2016 that made local results highly sensitive to the searcher's exact location and introduced address-based filtering. <strong>Multiple businesses at the same address targeting the same keywords now get filtered</strong> — only one typically appears in the local pack per query.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Released</div>
            <div class="tms-value">September 2016</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO Algorithm</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Primary impact</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Location-based filtering</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Named by the SEO community for listings that appeared to "play dead" and vanish from results, the Possum Update fundamentally changed the geography of local rankings. Where you search from now determines what local results you see.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is the Google Possum Update?</h2>
        <p>The Google Possum Update was released in September 2016 without an official Google announcement. The name was coined by the SEO community after observing listings disappear and reappear depending on searcher location — like an opossum playing dead.</p>
        <p>Two mechanisms define Possum:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Location-based variation.</strong> Local pack results shifted from relatively static metro-area displays to dynamic, location-sensitive outcomes. Searching "dentist near me" from the north side of Dallas now returns different businesses than the same search from the south side.</li>
          <li><strong>Address-based filtering.</strong> Multiple businesses sharing a physical address and targeting overlapping keywords get filtered — typically only one appears in the local pack per query. The filtered business isn't penalised; it simply doesn't appear for that particular searcher or keyword combination.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Important distinction</div>
          <p>Possum filtering only affects the local pack — the 3-result map box at the top of local search results. Organic web results below the pack were not changed. A filtered business can still rank organically and still appears when the search is slightly varied.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why does the Google Possum Update matter?</h2>
        <p>Possum permanently changed how you must think about local rank tracking and strategy. Four specific implications:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Rankings now vary by searcher location.</strong> Your rank 1 position from your business address means nothing about how you appear to a customer two miles away. You may be invisible to half your service area.</li>
          <li><strong>Suburban businesses gained ground.</strong> Pre-Possum, downtown businesses dominated because Google centered local results on city centres. Post-Possum, a business in a suburban location now ranks well for nearby searchers without competing against downtown authority.</li>
          <li><strong>Shared addresses became liabilities.</strong> Virtual offices, co-working spaces, and multi-business suites saw their listings filtered. Two lawyers at the same address targeting "personal injury attorney [city]" compete for the single local pack slot.</li>
          <li><strong>Geo-grid tracking became essential.</strong> Single-point rank tracking (checking from one location) became meaningless. Accurate local SEO monitoring requires checking rankings across a grid of locations across your service area.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How the Google Possum Update works</h2>
        <p>Possum operates through three interconnected mechanisms:</p>
        <h3>Location-based result variation</h3>
        <p>Google calculates distance from the searcher's device coordinates to each business location. The weighting of that distance signal increased substantially with Possum. A 4-mile radius dentist visibility in pre-Possum local results shrank to a 2-mile effective radius in many markets post-Possum.</p>
        <h3>Address filtering logic</h3>
        <p>When two businesses share an address and both optimise for similar primary categories or keywords, Google filters one out of the local pack for any given query. The filter is not a penalty — the filtered business still has a live GBP and can appear for different keyword variations or from different searcher locations.</p>
        <h3>Category and keyword interaction</h3>
        <p>Filtering decisions are influenced by primary GBP category, service keywords, and the degree of category overlap between co-located businesses. A law firm and an accountancy at the same address may each appear in their respective category searches — the filtering triggers when categories overlap.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Possum filtering scenarios — what triggers it</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
