        <h2 id="examples">Real Google Possum Update examples</h2>
        <h3>Example 1 — The vanishing listing</h3>
        <p>A marketing agency shared office space with two other marketing firms at a downtown address. After Possum, all three were filtered in rotation — each appearing for some queries and disappearing for others. The agency relocated to a unique address and recovered stable local pack presence within 60 days.</p>
        <h3>Example 2 — Suburban dentist gains on downtown competitor</h3>
        <p>A dentist practice in a suburb 4 miles from the city centre had been outranked by downtown practices for all "dentist near me" queries before Possum. Post-update, the practice ranked in the local pack for searchers within 2 miles — capturing the suburban patient base it had been invisible to before.</p>
        <h3>Example 3 — Geo-grid reveals invisible zones</h3>
        <p>A plumber tracking rankings from their office address showed position 1 for "emergency plumber [city]." A geo-grid check revealed they were invisible to searchers in 60% of their service area. Targeting location-specific content and citation building for underperforming zones improved coverage to 80% of the service area within 4 months.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Google Possum Update vs Google Vicinity Update — which matters more now</h2>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Possum (2016)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Results vary by exact searcher location</li>
              <li>Address-based filtering for co-located businesses</li>
              <li>Suburban businesses gained visibility</li>
              <li>Geo-grid tracking became necessary</li>
              <li>Primary category differentiation matters</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Vicinity (2021)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Proximity reweighted as dominant local signal</li>
              <li>Keyword stuffed GBP names penalised</li>
              <li>Nearby businesses with less optimisation can outrank</li>
              <li>Service area declarations mattered less</li>
              <li>Physical closeness to searcher became primary</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for the post-Possum local landscape</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Use geo-grid rank tracking.</strong> Tools like Local Falcon, Local Viking, or BrightLocal's grid tracker show your ranking at dozens of points across your service area — not just from your address. Do this before any optimisation so you know where your invisible zones are.</li>
          <li><strong>Secure a unique physical address.</strong> If you're using a shared office or virtual office, Possum filtering will suppress your listing regularly. A unique, verifiable address is the cleanest fix.</li>
          <li><strong>Differentiate GBP categories from co-located businesses.</strong> If you must share an address, ensure your primary category is clearly distinct from co-tenants. A plumber and an electrician at the same address filter less than two plumbers.</li>
          <li><strong>Build prominence signals across your service area.</strong> Reviews, citations, and local content that mention specific neighbourhoods and service areas reduce the impact of proximity-based filtering by strengthening your overall local authority.</li>
          <li><strong>Target location-specific content.</strong> Blog posts covering hyper-local topics — "best dentist in [neighbourhood]" — signal relevance to Google for areas outside your immediate proximity radius.</li>
          <li><strong>Keep GBP categories accurate and specific.</strong> Possum uses category data in filtering decisions. Broad or inaccurate categories increase the chance of being filtered alongside unrelated co-located businesses.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — single-location rank tracking</div>
          <p>Checking your rank from one location (your office or home) tells you almost nothing post-Possum. A rank-1 result at your address may be rank-7 or invisible two miles away. Always use geo-grid tools before reporting local SEO results to clients or stakeholders.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common mistakes businesses make after Possum</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Using virtual office addresses.</strong> Virtual offices shared by many businesses are high-risk for Possum filtering. The suppression compounds when other tenants target similar keywords.</li>
          <li><strong>Not differentiating GBP categories.</strong> Businesses at shared addresses need clearly distinct primary categories. Co-located law firms both using "Personal Injury Attorney" as primary category will both get filtered.</li>
          <li><strong>Treating rank-1 at one location as overall success.</strong> Your ranking from the office address is a single data point, not a performance metric. Geo-grid visibility is the real metric.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring the organic results.</strong> Possum only affects the local pack. Building strong organic rankings means you appear below the local pack even when filtered from it.</li>
          <li><strong>Creating duplicate GBP listings.</strong> Multiple listings for the same business trigger aggressive filtering. Audit your GBP regularly for duplicates and merge them.</li>
        </ul>

